{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a04e946-9168-4cfe-9133-58317e4b9b67","content":"The bug is on line 29 — `ProcessPayment` only checks for zero, not negatives. The fastest workflow is **`dotnet watch test`**, which auto-reruns tests on every file save — no manual rebuild needed.\n\nLet me fix the bug and set up the watcher:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01GFsAee1ejEwkKW4qiqmGio","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Fixing payment validation"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01JcfDsmuUekxYUWvHd1thRQ","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-7a167bfa99de43409458dd84e1eea017/PaymentProcessorTests.cs","old_str":"        if (amount == 0) throw new ArgumentException(\"Amount cannot be zero\");\n        // Missing: validation for negative amounts","new_str":"        if (amount <= 0) throw new ArgumentException(\"Amount must be positive\");"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-7a167bfa99de43409458dd84e1eea017/PaymentProcessorTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"be5fae6a-510d-4f08-9465-4adeb881d12d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The bug is clear: `ProcessPayment` only checks for `amount == 0` but doesn't check for negative amounts. The test on line 24 expects an `ArgumentException` for `-50.00m`, but the method just returns `true`.\n\nThe fix is to add `amount < 0` (or `amount <= 0`) to the validation. But the user is asking about the fastest workflow for iterating. The answer is `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests automatically on file save.\n\nLet me first fix the bug, then set up `dotnet watch test` for them.","outputTokens":412,"requestId":"7C44:2B65A1:28ED457:2D52941:69F9498A"},"id":"846a7e43-23b3-4f9f-9301-8b5e96d8f291","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:36:18.703Z","parentId":"562e790b-1c28-4529-80c4-91de5725ccf6"}
